"C4","C5"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cervical vertebra with a \u003Cstrong\u003Elonger, non-bifid spinous process\u003C/strong\u003E is C7, also known as the vertebra prominens. This distinguishes it from the typical cervical vertebrae (C3-C6), which have short, bifid spinous processes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC2\u003C/strong\u003E (the axis) has a bifid spinous process, whilst \u003Cstrong\u003EC3\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EC4\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003EC5\u003C/strong\u003E all have short, bifid spinous processes characteristic of typical cervical vertebrae. C7\u0027s prominent spinous process is a key anatomical landmark in the cervical region.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The spinous process of the seventh cervical vertebra (C7) is longer and not bifid, unlike the typical cervical vertebrae.","C7 is often referred to as the vertebra prominens due to its prominent spinous process.","Typical cervical vertebrae (C3-C6) have short, bifid spinous processes."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"da